If our other evidence were more questionable than it is, the decline of literature would alone confirm it. Not but that even the Augustan age is nearly stripped of literary genius, as the great spirits born and trained under the Republic pass away, and the few survivors at the succession of Tiberius attest by their position the change of times. The great historian of Rome had, as it seems, abruptly closed his work, and retired to his native Padua3 the only great living poet was pining in exile on the Euxine.
